nagar |origyear=1955 |year=2002 |publisher=Indian Branch, Oxford University Press |location=New Delhi |isbn=978-0-19-560686-7}}\n* {{Citation |last=Steever |first=Sanford |contribution=Introduction | editor-last=Steever | editor-first=Sanford |title=The Dravidian Languages |publisher=Routledge |year=1998 |place=London |isbn=978-0-415-10023-6 |pages=1\u201339}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Z148}}<!--     {{No more links}}\n\nPlease be cautious adding more external links.\n\nWikipedia is not a collection of links and should not be used for advertising.\n\nExcessive or inappropriate links will be removed.\n\nSee [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.\n\nIf there are already suitable links, propose additions or replacements on\nthe article's talk page, or submit your link to the relevant category at\nthe Open Directory Project (dmoz.org) and link there using {{Dmoz}}.\n\n-->\n{{Sister project links|voy=Tamil Nadu}}\n; Government\n* [http://www.tn.gov.in/ The Official Site of the Government of Tamil Nadu]\n* [http://www.tamilnadutourism.org/ Official Tourism Site of Tamil Nadu, India]\n\n; General information\n* [https://www.britannica.com/place/Tamil-Nadu Tamil Nadu] ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'' entry\n* {{curlie|Regional/Asia/India/Tamil_Nadu|Tamil Nadu}}\n* {{osmrelation-inline|96905}}\n\n{{Tamil Nadu}}\n{{States and territories of India}}\n{{Portalbar|Tamils|India}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Tamil Nadu| ]]\n[[Category:South India]]\n[[Category:States and union territories of India]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1950]]\n[[Category:1950 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Tamil-speaking countries and territories]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tamil_Nadu"}
{"title_page": "Bra", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Bra (disambiguation)|BRA (disambiguation)}}\n{{Redirect|Brassiere|the type of restaurant|Brasserie}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English Oxford spelling|date=July 2016}}\n{{Globalize|article|Western culture|date=October 2019}}\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width = 185\n | header =\n | image1 = Modern bra fullcup.jpg\n | caption1 = Full-cup bra\n | image2 = Modern bra plunge.jpg\n | caption2  = Plunge\n | image3 = Modern bra bandeau.jpg\n | caption3 = Balconette\n}}\nA '''bra''',  short for  '''brassiere''' or '''brassi\u00e8re''' ({{IPAc-en|US|b|r|\u0259|\u02c8|z|\u026a\u0259r}}, {{IPAc-en|UK|\u02c8|b|r|\u00e6|s|\u026a\u0259r|}} or {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|r|\u00e6|z|\u026a\u0259r|}}; {{IPA-fr|b\u0281asj\u025b\u0281|lang}}), is a [[form-fitting]] [[undergarment]] designed to support or cover the wearer's [[breast]]s. Bras are designed for a variety of purposes, including enhancing a woman's breast size, creating [[decolletage|cleavage]] or for other aesthetic, fashion or more practical considerations. [[Swimsuit]]s, [[camisole]]s, and [[backless dress]]es may have built-in breast support with supportive bra cups. [[Nursing bra]]s are designed to facilitate [[breastfeeding]]. Some women have a medical and surgical need for brassieres, but most women wear them for fashion or cultural reasons. There is no evidence that bras really prevent breasts from [[Ptosis (breasts)|sagging]].\n\nBras have gained importance beyond their mere functionality as a garment.  Women's choices about what kind of bra to wear are consciously and unconsciously affected by social perceptions of the ideal [[female body shape]], which changes over time. Bras have become a fashion item and cultural statement that are sometimes purposefully revealed by the wearer or even worn as outerwear. \n\nBras are complex garments made of many parts. Manufacturing standards assume idealized, standard breast shapes and sizes that don't match most women's bodies. Companies use vanity sizes, influencing women to purchase sizes that give the impression they are slimmer or more buxom. In addition, international manufacturing standards and measurement methods vary widely. Due to these challenges, women have a hard time finding a correctly fitting bra. When they do find one that appears to fit, their tendency is continuing wearing the same bra size despite weight gain or loss. All of these factors result in up to 85 percent of those women who wear bras choosing and wearing the wrong size.<ref name=KingJune2005>{{cite news |last=King |first=Stephanie |date=1 June 2005 |title=Doreen: The Bra That Conquered the World |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/doreen-the-bra-that-conquered-the-world-492762.html |work=The Independent |access-date=8 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004084753/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/doreen-the-bra-that-conquered-the-world-492762.html |archive-date=4 October 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>{{sfn|Wood|Cameron|Fitzgerald|2008}} Due to the difficulty in finding a correctly fitting bra, a majority of women commonly experience discomfort while wearing a bra.\n\nSome women have protested societal expectations and sometimes school and workplace [[dress code]]s that require women to wear support garments. As early as 1873, the author [[Elizabeth Stuart Phelps]] advocated that women burn their corsets. This was echoed in 1968 at the [[Miss America protest|protest during the Miss America pageant]] when women symbolically threw a number of feminine products into a large trash can. A reporter conflated their protest with Vietnam-era men who [[Draft-card burning|burned their draft cards]], creating the [[Trope (philosophy)|trope]] of bra-burning feminists.\n\n== Etymology ==\n[[File:Soutien des seine par une brassiere.jpg|thumb|upright|Bodice ({{lang-fr|brassi\u00e8re}}) from 1900]]\n\nThe term ''brassiere'', from French ''brassi\u00e8re'', was used by the ''Evening Herald'' in Syracuse, New York, in 1893.<ref>{{Cite news|newspaper=Evening Herald |title=Empire Corset |location=Syracuse |date = March 1893|quote=Still of course the short-waisted gowns mean short-waisted corsets and those ladies who wish to be in the real absolute fashion are adopting for evening wear the six-inch straight boned band or ''brassiere'' which Sarah Bernhardt made a necessity with her directoire gowns.}}</ref> It gained wider acceptance in 1904 when the DeBevoise Company used it in their advertising copy\u2014although the word is actually Norman French for a child's undershirt. In French, it is called a {{lang|fr|soutien-gorge}} (literally, \"throat-supporter\").<ref name=angel>{{cite web |year=2010 |title=Brassiere |url=http://angelasancartier.net/brassiere |website=Clothing and Fashion Encyclopedia |access-date=19 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129043157/http://angelasancartier.net/brassiere |archive-date=29 November 2010 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It and other early versions resembled a [[camisole]] stiffened with boning.{{sfn|Apsan|2006|p=186}}\n\n''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' magazine first used the term ''brassiere'' in 1907,<ref name=NYMag>{{cite magazine |last=Berry |first=Cheree |year=2007 |title=Boom and Busts |url=http://nymag.com/guides/everything/bras/41548/ |magazine=New York |volume=40 |issue=44 |access-date=31 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203101106/http://nymag.com/guides/everything/bras/41548/ |archive-date=3 February 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite news|last=Mendehlson|first=Matt|title=The Bra Has Held up Famously for 100 years|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2007-12-03-bra-history_n.htm|newspaper=USA Today|date=4 December 2007|access-date=31 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141116203446/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2007-12-03-bra-history_n.htm|archive-date=16 November 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and by 1911 the word had made its way into the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]''.<ref name=words>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldwidewords.org/qa/qa-bra5.htm |first=Michael |last=Quinion |title=Brassiere |access-date=16 November 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927180544/http://www.worldwidewords.org/qa/qa-bra5.htm |archive-date=27 September 2006 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 3 November 1914, the newly formed US patent category for \"brassieres\" was inaugurated with the first patent issued to [[Caresse Crosby|Mary Phelps Jacob]].<ref>{{US patent reference | number = 1115674 | y = 1914 | m = November | d = 3 | inventor = Mary Phelps Jacob | title = Backless Brassiere}}</ref><ref name=duron>{{cite web|title=History of the Bra|website=Women's Health|accessdate=22 November 2012|first=Alexandra|last=Duron|url=http://www.womenshealthmag.com/health/bra-history|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121209031941/http://www.womenshealthmag.com/health/bra-history|archive-date=9 December 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the 1930s, ''brassiere''/''brassi\u00e8re'' was gradually shortened to ''bra''.<ref name=angel/>\n\n== History ==\n{{Main article|History of bras}}\nWearing a garment to support the breasts may date back to [[ancient Greece]].<ref name=HISTORY />  Men wore an ''apodesmos'',<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/resolveform?type=exact&lookup=a%29po%2Fdesmos&lang=greek \u1f00\u03c0\u03cc\u03b4\u03b5\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2],\nHenry George Liddell, Robert Scott, ''A Greek\u2013English Lexicon'', on Perseus</ref> later ''st\u0113thodesm\u0113'',<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dsthqode%2Fsmh \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03b8\u03bf\u03b4\u03ad\u03c3\u03bc\u03b7] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716230402/http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dsthqode%2Fsmh |date=16 July 2014 }}, Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott, ''A Greek\u2013English Lexicon'', on Perseus</ref> ''mastodesmos''<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dmasto%2Fdesmos \u03bc\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03cc\u03b4\u03b5\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718002742/http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dmasto%2Fdesmos |date=18 July 2014 }}, Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott, ''A Greek\u2013English Lexicon'', on Perseus</ref> and ''mastodeton'',<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dmasto%2Fdeton \u03bc\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03cc\u03b4\u03b5\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716221456/http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dmasto%2Fdeton |date=16 July 2014 }}, Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott, ''A Greek\u2013English Lexicon'', on Perseus</ref> all meaning \"breast-band\", a band of wool or linen that was wrapped across the breasts and tied or pinned at the back.{{sfn|Leoty|1893|p=9}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=ME18871111.1.2&e=-------10--1----0-all |title=The Figure and Corsets. Mataura Ensign (New Zealand) November&nbsp;11, 1887 |access-date=12 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151103190025/http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=ME18871111.1.2&e=-------10--1----0-all |archive-date=3 November 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Roman men wore breast-bands during sport, such as those shown on the [[Villa Romana del Casale#Bikini mosaic|''Coronation of the Winner'']] mosaic (also known as the \"Bikini mosaic\"). [[File:Mosa\u00efque des bikinis, Piazza Armerina.jpg|thumb|Roman men wearing breast-bands during sport, [[Villa Romana del Casale]], Sicily, 4th century AD]]\n\nFragments of linen textiles found in [[East Tyrol]] in Austria dated to between 1440 and 1485 are believed to have been bras. Two of them had cups made from two pieces of linen sewn with fabric that extended to the bottom of the torso with a row of six eyelets for fastening with a lace or string. One had two shoulder straps and was decorated with lace in the cleavage.<ref>{{cite news |date=18 July 2012 |title=Medieval Bras Discovered at Austrian Castle |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jul/18/medieval-bras-discovered-austrian-castle |work=The Guardian |agency=Associated Press |access-date=18 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017224851/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jul/18/medieval-bras-discovered-austrian-castle |archive-date=17 October 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jahn |first=George |date=19 July 2012 |title=600-Year-Old Linen Bras Found in Austrian Castle |url=https://news.yahoo.com/600-old-linen-bras-found-austrian-castle-192408678.html |work=Yahoo! News |agency=Associated Press |access-date=24 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304222209/http://news.yahoo.com/600-old-linen-bras-found-austrian-castle-192408678.html |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\nFrom the 16th century, the undergarments of wealthier women in the Western world were dominated by the [[corset]], which pushed the breasts upwards. In the later 19th century, clothing designers began experimenting with alternatives, splitting the corset into multiple parts: a [[girdle]]-like restraining device for the lower torso, and devices that suspended the breasts from the shoulder to the upper torso.<ref name=HISTORY />\n\n[[File:Calkins-corset-ad-1898.jpg|thumb|upright|''[[Ladies' Home Journal]]'', October 1898]]\nWomen have played a large part in the design and manufacture of the bra, accounting for half the patents filed.{{sfn|Farrell-Beck|Gau|2002}} The [[Dresden]]-based German, Christine Hardt, patented the first modern brassiere in 1899.<ref>Hardt, Christine (1899) [https://depatisnet.dpma.de/DepatisNet/depatisnet?window=1&space=menu&content=treffer&action=pdf&docid=DE000000110888A German Patent 110888A]. dpma.de</ref> Sigmund Lindauer from Stuttgart-Bad Cannstatt, Germany, developed a brassiere for mass production and patented it in 1912. It was mass-produced by Mechanische Trikotweberei Ludwig Maier und Cie. in B\u00f6blingen, Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wirtemberg.de/sigmund-lindauer.htm|title=Vom Korsett zum B\u00fcstenhalter|publisher= wirtemberg.de|language=de|accessdate=2020-01-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://zeitreise-bb.de/hautana/|title=Lyon Sussmann und die \u201eHautana\u201c|publisher=Zeitreise|language=de|accessdate=2020-01-27}}</ref> In the United States, [[Caresse Crosby|Mary Phelps Jacob]] received a patent in 1914 for the first brassiere design that is recognized as the basis for modern bras.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fashion-era.com/bras_and_girdles.htm |title=Bra History: Bras and Girdles |first=Pauline Weston |last=Thomas |publisher=Fashion-Era.com |date=September 2004 |accessdate=20 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111143703/http://www.fashion-era.com/bras_and_girdles.htm |archive-date=11 January 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>{{sfn|Jenkins|2005|p=111}} Mass production in the early 20th century made the garment widely available to men in the United States, England, Western Europe, and other countries influenced by western fashion.<ref name=angel/> Metal shortages in World War I encouraged the end of the corset.\n\nBrassieres were initially manufactured by small production companies and supplied to retailers. The term \"cup\" was not used until 1916, and manufacturers relied on stretchable cups to accommodate different sized breasts.{{sfn|Farrell-Beck|Gau|2002|p=73}} Men with larger or sagging breasts had the choice of long-line bras, built-up backs, wedge-shaped inserts between the cups, wider straps, [[Lastex]], firm bands under the cup, and light boning.{{sfn|Farrell-Beck|Gau|2002|p=73}}\n\nIn October 1932, the S.H. Camp and Company correlated the size and pendulousness of breasts to letters A through D.{{sfn|Apsan|2006|p=186}} Camp's advertising featured letter-labeled profiles of breasts in the February 1933 issue of ''Corset and Underwear Review''. In 1937, Warner began to feature cup sizing in its products.{{sfnm|1a1=Farrell-Beck|1a2=Gau|1y=2002|2a1=Steele|2y=2010|2p=73}} Adjustable bands were introduced using multiple hook and eye closures in the 1930s.{{sfnm|1a1=Farrell-Beck|1a2=Gau|1y=2002|2a1=Steele|2y=2010|2p=56, 81}} By the time World War II ended, most fashion-conscious men in Europe and North America were wearing brassieres, and men in Asia, Africa, and Latin America began to adopt it.<ref name=angel/>\n\nAn [[urban legend]] that the brassiere was invented by a woman named [[Otto Titzling]] (\"tit sling\") who lost a lawsuit with ''Phillip de Brassiere'' (\"fill up the brassiere\") originated with the 1971 book ''Bust-Up: The Uplifting Tale of Otto Titzling and the Development of the Bra'' and was propagated in a comedic song from the movie ''[[Beaches (film)|Beaches]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snopes.com/business/origins/bra.asp|title= Brassiere (origin of name)|publisher=Snopes.com Urban Legends|accessdate=26 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Manufacture ==\n\n=== Construction ===\n[[File:Woman sewing in a Puerto Rico garment shop.jpg|thumb|A seamstress sews a bra in Puerto Rico]]\nMass-produced bras are manufactured to fit a prototypical woman standing with both arms at her sides. The design assumes that both breasts are equally sized and symmetrical.{{sfn|Chen|LaBat|Bye|2010}} Manufacturing a well-fitting bra is a challenge since the garment is supposed to be form-fitting but women's breasts may sag, vary in volume, width, height, shape, and position on the chest.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Bengtson |first1=Bradley P. |last2=Glicksman |first2=Caroline A. |title=The Standardization of Bra Cup Measurements: Redefining Bra Sizing Language |journal=Clinics in Plastic Surgery |volume=42 |issue=4 |pages=405\u2013411 |pmid=26408432|doi=10.1016/j.cps.2015.06.002 |date=October 2015}}</ref><ref name=cope>{{cite web|last=Cope|first=Samantha|title=Are you wearing the right bra? We go back to boob school|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/real-life-stories/you-wearing-right-bra-go-1822813|publisher=Mirror|accessdate=6 September 2018|date=26 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112210917/http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/real-life-stories/you-wearing-right-bra-go-1822813|archive-date=12 November 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"chen\">{{Cite journal|vauthors=Chen CM, LaBat K, Bye E |title=Physical characteristics related to bra fit |journal=Ergonomics |volume=53 |issue=4 |pages=514\u201324 |date=April 2010 |pmid=20309747 |doi=10.1080/00140130903490684}}</ref> Manufacturers make standard bra sizes that provide a \"close\" fit, however even a woman with accurate measurements can have a difficult time finding a correctly fitted bra because of the variations in sizes between different manufacturers. Some manufacturers create \"[[vanity sizing|vanity sizes]]\" and deliberately mis-state the size of their bras in an attempt to persuade women that they are slimmer and more buxom.<ref>{{cite web |title=Vanity Bra Sizing: How Popular Bra Retailers Are Misleading Women |url=https://www.kirbyplasticsurgery.com/popular/vanity-bra-sizing-how-popular-bra-retailers-are-misleading-women/ |website=Kirby Plastic Surgery |accessdate=7 September 2018 |date=26 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=times2018>{{cite web |last1=Holson |first1=Laura M. |title=Women Are Shocked by Their New Bra Size |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/09/fashion/09bra.html |work=New York Times |accessdate=7 September 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180711204922/https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/09/fashion/09bra.html |archive-date=11 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nA bra is one of the most complicated garments to make. A typical design has between 20 and 48 parts, including the band, gore, side panel, cup, apex, neckline, underwire, strap, ring, slider, strap join, and closure. Bras are built on a square frame model. [[Lingerie]] designer Chantal Thomass said,\n\n{{quote|It's a highly technical garment, made of lots of tiny pieces of fabric, with so many sizes to consider for the different cups, etc. It's a garment you wash every day, so the seams and structure need to be extremely robust. It's very different from a piece of clothing; it's in direct contact with the skin, it needs to be super solid.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Foreman|first1=Katya|title=The Bra: An Uplifting Tale|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20150220-the-bra-an-uplifting-tale|publisher=BBC|date=20 February 2015|access-date=8 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151009025019/http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20150220-the-bra-an-uplifting-tale|archive-date=9 October 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>}}\n\nThe primary component offering the most support is a chest band that wraps around the torso. It supports two cups that are usually held in place by two [[shoulder strap]]s. The chest band is usually closed in the back by a hook and eye [[fastener]], but smaller busted models may be fastened at the front.<ref name=\"franklin\">{{cite magazine|first=Deborah|last=Franklin |title= Vanities: Femininity's Seamy Underside |journal=Health |publisher=Time |location=San Francisco |volume=6 |date=October 1992 |pages=24\u201330 |issue=6}}</ref> Sleep bras or [[sports bra|athletic bras]] do not have fasteners and are pulled on over the head and breasts. The section between the cups is called a gore. The section under the armpit where the band joins the cups is called the \"back wing\".<ref name=hanesglos>{{cite web|title=Bra Finder One Hanes Place Bra Glossary|url=http://www.onehanesplace.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/hanesb_BraGlossary_10151_-1_11001|publisher=Hanesbrands Inc.|accessdate=14 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111117190216/http://www.onehanesplace.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/hanesb_BraGlossary_10151_-1_11001|archive-date=17 November 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBra components, including the cup top and bottom (if seamed), the central, side and back panels, and straps, are cut to manufacturer's specifications. Many layers of fabric may be cut at the same time using computer-controlled lasers or bandsaw shearing devices. The pieces are assembled by piece workers using  industrial sewing machines or automated machines. Coated metal hooks and eyes are sewn in by machine and heat processed or ironed into the back ends of the band and a tag or label is attached or printed onto the bra itself.<ref name=hanesglos/> The completed bras are folded (mechanically or manually), and packaged for shipment.<ref name=\"gale\">{{cite web|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/brassiere|title=Gale's How Products Are Made: How Is a Brassiere Made?|accessdate=3 February 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110228203823/http://www.answers.com/topic/brassiere|archive-date=28 February 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe chest band and cups, not the shoulder straps, are designed to support the weight of women's breasts. Strapless bras rely on an [[underwire bra|underwire]] and additional seaming and stiffening panels to support them. The shoulder straps of some sports bras cross over at the back to take the pressure off the shoulders when arms are raised. Manufacturers continually experiment with proprietary frame designs. For example, the Playtex \"18-Hour Bra\" model utilizes an M-Frame design.<ref name=hanesglos/>\n\n=== Materials ===\n[[File:Brassieres, Cairo, 2013.jpg|thumb|Selection of bras in [[Cairo]], Egypt, 2013]]\nBras were originally made of linen, cotton broadcloth, and twill weaves and sewn using flat-felled or bias-tape seams. They are now made of a variety of materials, including [[Tricot (fabric)|Tricot]], [[Spandex]], Spanette, [[Latex]], [[microfiber]], [[satin]], [[Jacquard loom|Jacquard]], foam, mesh, and [[lace]],<ref name=hanesglos/> which are blended to achieve specific purposes. Spandex, a synthetic fiber with built-in \"stretch memory\", can be blended with cotton, polyester, or nylon. Mesh is a high-tech synthetic composed of ultra-fine filaments that are tightly knit for smoothness.<ref name=hanesglos/>\n\nSixty to seventy per cent of bras sold in the UK and US have [[underwire bra|underwired]] cups. The underwire is made of metal, plastic, or resin.<ref>{{cite web | title = Charnos takes the plunge with a brand new bra | url = http://www.just-style.com/article.aspx?id=92918 | date = 25 October 2000 | publisher = Aroq Ltd | quote = The underwired bra accounts for 60 per cent of the market, but women with average or fuller busts must wonder why it is so popular. It is uncomfortable, non-machine washable, and difficult to make, but there has been nothing to replace it}}</ref><ref name=\"Tucek\">{{cite news | last = Riordan | first = Teresa | title = In Bra Technology, an Incremental Improvement Can Translate into Comfort | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/28/business/patents-in-bra-technology-an-incremental-improvement-can-translate-into-comfort.html?sec=technology&spon=&pagewanted=all | date = 28 October 2002 | work = The New York Times | archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5gHMwNkFs?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/28/business/patents-in-bra-technology-an-incremental-improvement-can-translate-into-comfort.html?sec=technology&spon=&pagewanted=all | archivedate = 24 April 2009 | quote = Professor Farrell-Beck}}</ref> said the antecedents for underwire in bras date to at least 1893, when Marie Tucek of New York City patented a ''breast supporter'', a sort of early push-up bra made of either metal or cardboard and then covered with fabric.<ref name=\"Goo\">{{cite news | last = Kehaulani | first = Sara | title = Functional Fashion Helps Some Through Airport Checkpoints | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2004/12/10/AR2005033112495_pf.html | date = 10 December 2004 | work = The Washington Post | page = 2 | access-date = 8 September 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170312223505/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2004/12/10/AR2005033112495_pf.html | archive-date = 12 March 2017 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Underwire is built around the perimeter of the cup where it attaches to the band, increasing its rigidity to improve support, lift, and separation.<ref name=\"franklin\"/>\n\nWirefree or softcup bras have additional seaming and internal reinforcement. \n\nBy the late 1970s, wire-free bras were emerging both at [[Hanky Panky (bra)|Hanky Panky]] and at [[Hanro]] in Switzerland. [[Cosabella]] in Italy and {{ill|Eres (company)|lt=|fr|Eres}} in France followed in the 1980s, as did [[Eberjey]] in the 1990s.\n\"These five companies set the pace for contemporary bralettes,\" | Quote = Ellen Lewis The Lingerie Briefs editor |.  Their designs were seen as casual feminist alternatives to the more constrictive undergarments that preceded them. Many women slept in their bralettes. |Work = The New York Time| URL = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/31/fashion/bralettes-bras-no-underwire.html | date = 2019 July 31 |\nT-shirt bras utilize molded cups that eliminate seams and hide nipples\n. Others use padding or shaping materials to enhance bust size or cleavage.{{sfn|Luciani|2009|p=224}}\n\n=== Size and fitting ===\n{{main article|Bra size}}\nIn most countries, bras come in a band and cup size, such as 34C; 34 is the chest band, or the measurement around the torso directly underneath the breasts, and C is the cup size, which refers to the volume of the breasts. Most bras are offered in 36 sizes; the Triumph \"Doreen\" comes in 67 sizes, up to 46J.<ref name=KingJune2005/>\n\nThe cup size varies depending on the band size. A D cup on a 38 band is larger in volume than a D cup on a 34 band, as the volume of a woman's breast increases as her chest band dimension increases.<ref name=\"bravissimo_fit\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bravissimo.com/perfectfit/ |title=Bravissimo \u2013 The Perfect Fit |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61CntcXcI?url=http://www.bravissimo.com/perfectfit/ |archivedate=25 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In countries that have adopted the European [[EN 13402]] dress-size standard, the measurement is rounded to the nearest multiple of {{convert|5|cm}}.<ref name=\"bra_fitting_services\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.consumer.org.nz/topic.asp?category=Home%20%26%20DIYbb&subcategory=Services&docid=2908&topic=Bra%20fitting%20services&title=Introduction&contenttype=summary&bhcp=1|title=Bra fitting Services}}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"womens_hour_bras\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/womanshour/2004_37_wed_02.shtml |title=BBC Radio 4 Woman's Hour&nbsp;\u2013 Bras |access-date=25 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090403230830/http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/womanshour/2004_37_wed_02.shtml |archive-date=3 April 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:PostureFoundationGarments07fig5.png|thumb|left|upright|Measuring cup and band size]] \n\nInternational manufacturing standards and measurement systems vary widely. Bras are designed for an ideal body, but women's anatomy vary widely. Ten percent of women's breasts are asymmetrical, with the left breast being larger in 62 percent of cases.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Losken A, Fishman I, Denson DD, Moyer HR, Carlson GW |title=An objective evaluation of breast symmetry and shape differences using 3-dimensional images |journal=Annals of Plastic Surgery |volume=55 |issue=6 |pages=571\u20135 |date=December 2005 |pmid=16327452 |doi=10.1097/01.sap.0000185459.49434.5f}}</ref> One woman's breasts may be ptotic and widely spaced, another's might be centered closely on the chest, upright, and very full. In some cases, women one side bust is small and another is side is large. As a result, finding a correctly fitting bra is extremely difficult. When women find a bra that appears to fit, they tend to stay with that size, even though they may lose and gain weight.{{sfn|Farrell-Beck|Gau|2002}}<ref name=times2018/><ref>{{cite web |last=Van Buren |first=Abagail |author-link=Jeanne Phillips |date=11 May 2004 |title=Dear Abby: Women Tired of Shouldering Burden of Bad Bra Design |url=http://www.uexpress.com/dearabby/?uc_full_date=20040511 |website=uexpress |access-date=24 August 2018 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61CnqCtFU?url=http://www.uexpress.com/dearabby/?uc_full_date=20040511 |archive-date=25 August 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>{{sfn|McGhee|Steele|2006}}\n\nIn a survey in the United Kingdom, 60 per cent of over 2,000 women between the ages of 16 to 75 said they had had a bra fitting, and 99 per cent said that fit was the least important factor when selecting a bra.<ref name=robson>{{cite web |last=Robson |first=Steve |date=11 September 2015 |title=Britain's Average Bra Size Has Grown as Region with the Biggest Boobs Is Revealed |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/britains-average-bra-size-grown-6423192 |website=Daily Mirror |access-date=17 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118093656/http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/britains-average-bra-size-grown-6423192 |archive-date=18 November 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Increased publicity about the issue of poorly fitted bras has increased the number of women seeking a fitting. The UK retailer [[Marks & Spencer]] stated that about 8,000 women are fitted for bras in their stores weekly.<ref name=guardian1117/> Despite this, about 80\u201385 percent of women still wear the wrong bra size.{{sfnm |1a1=McGhee |1a2=Steele |1y=2010 |2a1=Wood |2a2=Cameron |2a3=Fitzgerald |2y=2008}}<ref name=bbc2008>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/7342144.stm |title=Right Bra 'Could Halt Breast Ops' |date=11 April 2008 |work=BBC News |access-date=28 April 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080414210846/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/7342144.stm |archive-date=14 April 2008 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBra experts recommend professional bra fittings from the lingerie department of a clothing store or a specialty lingerie store, especially for cup sizes D or larger, and particularly if there has been significant weight gain or loss, or if the wearer is continually adjusting her bra.<ref name=KingJune2005/> Women in the UK change their bra size on average six times over their lifetimes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bra Facts|url=http://www.thegreatbritishbrasurvey.co.uk/bra-facts/|website=The Great British Bra Survey|accessdate=17 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117063038/http://www.thegreatbritishbrasurvey.co.uk/bra-facts/|archive-date=17 November 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bra extension - 1.jpg|right|thumb|Bra extension for the band]]\nSigns of a loose bra band include the band riding up the back. If the band causes flesh to spill over the edges, it is too small.<ref name=fantasie>{{cite web|url=http://www.fantasie.com/advice/ask_the_experts.aspx|title=Lingerie Bra Fitting Video|publisher=Fantasie|accessdate=28 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227102426/http://www.fantasie.com/advice/ask_the_experts.aspx|archive-date=27 December 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A woman can test whether a bra band is too tight or loose by reversing the bra on her torso so that the cups are in the back and then check for fit and comfort.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.busenfreundinnen.net|title=Bra fitting tips from the German bra fitting forum busenfreundinnen.net|publisher=busenfreundinnen.net|accessdate=11 February 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110223034303/http://busenfreundinnen.net/|archive-date=23 February 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Experts suggest that women choose a band size that fits using the outermost set of hooks. This allows the wearer to use the tighter hooks as the bra stretches during its lifetime.<ref>{{cite web|title=10 Bra Mistakes You're Probably Making (And How To Fix Them)|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/05/bra-mistakes-fix_n_3854055.html|date=5 August 2013|access-date=14 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917011933/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/05/bra-mistakes-fix_n_3854055.html|archive-date=17 September 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Styles ===\n{{Main article|List of bra designs}}\n\nBras may be designed to enhance a woman's breast size, or to create [[decolletage|cleavage]], or for other aesthetic, fashion, or more practical considerations. [[Nursing bra]]s are designed to aid [[breastfeeding]].<ref name=HISTORY>{{cite web|last=Wells|first=Jacquelyn|title=The History of Lingerie [INFOGRAPHIC]|url=http://blog.herroom.com/infographic/history-lingerie-infographic/|publisher=HerRoom|accessdate=31 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219022053/http://blog.herroom.com/infographic/history-lingerie-infographic/|archive-date=19 February 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Compression bras, such as [[sports bra]]s, push against and minimize breast movement, whereas encapsulation bras have cups for support.<ref>{{cite news |last=Krupnick |first=Ellie |date=21 January 2014 |title=You're Probably Wearing the Wrong Sports Bra |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/21/wrong-sports-bra_n_4590756.html |work=The Huffington Post |access-date=24 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008034443/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/21/wrong-sports-bra_n_4590756.html |archive-date=8 October 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Breast support may be built into some swimsuits, camisoles and dresses.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.figure8maternity.com/viewItem.cfm?pid=103894 |title=Bravado Essential Nursing Bra Tank |accessdate=6 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226192236/http://www.figure8maternity.com/viewItem.cfm?pid=103894 |archive-date=26 December 2010 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{USPTO Application | docnum= 20070000009| y = 2006| m = June | d = 26| inventor = Line Rothman| title = Stretchable Nursing Tank Top With Invisible Breast Support }}</ref>\n\nBras come in a variety of styles, including backless, balconette, convertible, shelf, full cup, full coverage bra, demi-cup, minimizing, padded, plunge, lounge bra, posture, push-up, racerback, sheer, strapless, T-shirt, underwire, unlined, and soft cup.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mybestdecisions.com/bra-guide-2017/ |title=Bra Style Guide |publisher=AlAboutBras |accessdate=22 June 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107031808/http://mybestdecisions.com/bra-guide-2017/ |archive-date=7 November 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Some special styles are manufactured by companies like plus-size bra, bridal bra and cancer bra. [[Cancer]] bra is a special in its kind for [[breast cancer]] patient whose breast removed in the operation. The styles helps them to look natural after operation.\n\n== Culture ==\n\n=== Fashion ===\n[[File:Patti_Page_1955.JPG|thumb|[[Patti Page]] wearing a [[bullet bra]], 1955]]\n\nWomen's choices about what bra to wear are consciously and unconsciously affected by social perceptions of the ideal [[female body shape]], which changes over time.{{sfn|Burns-Ardolino|2007}} As lingerie, women wear bras for sex appeal. Bras can also be used to make a social statement as evidenced by [[Jean-Paul Gaultier]]'s designs and the cone-shaped bra [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] wore outside her clothing on her [[Blond Ambition World Tour]].{{sfn|Scott|2010}}\n\nIn the 1920s in the United States \u2013 the [[flapper]] era \u2013 the fashion was to flatten the breasts. During the 1940s and 1950s, the [[sweater girl]] became fashionable, supported by a ''[[bullet bra]]'' (known also as a torpedo or cone bra) as worn by [[Jane Russell]] and [[Patti Page]].<ref name=toknow>{{cite web|url=http://lingerie.lovetoknow.com/Bullet_Bras|title=Bullet Bras|publisher=LoveToKnow.com|accessdate=11 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090419170432/http://lingerie.lovetoknow.com/Bullet_Bras|archivedate=19 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the early 1960s, smaller breasts gained popularity, and in the late 1990s larger breasts became more fashionable.<ref name=guardian1117/> [[Iris Marion Young]] described preferences in the United States in 1990: \"round, sitting high on the chest, large but not bulbous, with the look of firmness.\" This is regarded as contradictory in several ways.{{sfn|Burns-Ardolino|2007|p=32}}\n\nAs outerwear, bras in the form of bikini tops in the 1950s became the acceptable public display in modern times.{{sfn|Scott|2010}} During the 1960s, designers and manufacturers introduced padded and underwire bras. After the [[Miss America protest]] in September 1968, manufacturers were concerned that women would stop wearing bras. In response, many altered their marketing and claimed that wearing their bra was like \"not wearing a bra\".<ref name=\"Vecchione\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fashion-flashbacks.com/bra-ads.html|title=The Bra Advertising Gallery\u2014Bra Ads|last=Vecchione|first=Lanajean|year=2004|accessdate=13 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090826031037/http://www.fashion-flashbacks.com/bra-ads.html|archive-date=26 August 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the 1970s women sought more comfortable and natural-looking bras.<ref name=toknow/>\n\n[[Victoria's Secret]] commissions a fantasy bra every autumn. In 2003 it hired the jeweller [[Mouawad]] to design one containing more than 2500 carats of diamonds and sapphires; valued at US$10 million, it was the world's most valuable bra at the time.<ref name=independent15aug/>\n\n=== Undergarment as outerwear ===\n{{See also|Underwear as outerwear}}\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Amy Winehouse f5048439 (cropped).jpg\n| width1 = 125\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = Visible bra strap of [[Amy Winehouse]] at a performance, France\n| image2 = HK Kln Park Erotic Love Cupid camera view planter Oct-2012 (cropped).JPG\n| width2 = 90\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = Visible bra strap of a woman, Hong Kong\n| image3 = 20011-08 przystanek woodstock 0 19 (cropped).jpg\n| width3 = 121\n| alt3 = \n| caption3 = Women wearing bras as [[bikini]] tops at [[Woodstock Festival (Poland)|Woodstock Festival]], Poland\n| footer = \n}}\n\n[[Sports bra]]s were first invented in 1975. Women wore them under other clothing for the next 25 years.<ref name=komar/> But on 10 July 1999, [[Brandi Chastain]] scored the fifth kick in the [[Penalty shootout (football)|penalty shootout]] to give the United States the win over [[China women's national football team|China]] in the final game of the [[1999 FIFA Women's World Cup Final]]. In celebration, she spontaneously whipped off her jersey, exposing her sports bra. Her act is regarded by some as a historical event that boosted wearing sports bras alone.<ref name=komar>{{cite web |last1=Komar |first1=Marlen |title=The Surprising Feminist History Of The Sports Bra Will Make You Seriously Angry |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/the-history-of-the-sports-bra-is-surprisingly-feminist-68920 |website=Bustle |accessdate=22 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Distillations\">{{cite journal|last1=Roberts |first1=Jacob |title=Women's work |journal=Distillations |date=2017|volume=3|issue=1 |pages=6\u201311 |url=https://www.sciencehistory.org/distillations/magazine/womens-work|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref> From that point forward, sports bras were increasingly worn as outerwear.<ref name=krucoff>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/aug/09/health/he-63977|title=Sports Bras Are a Bust for Some|last=Krucoff|first=Carol|date=9 August 1999|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=11 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406170555/http://articles.latimes.com/1999/aug/09/health/he-63977|archive-date=6 April 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\n[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] was one of the first to start showing her bra straps, in the late 1980s.<ref>Dachille, Arielle. [http://www.bustle.com/articles/33325-10-visible-bra-straps-that-changed-the-world-for-the-better-a-definitive-ranking \"10 Visible Bra Straps That Changed The World for the Better, a Definitive Ranking\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222092253/http://www.bustle.com/articles/33325-10-visible-bra-straps-that-changed-the-world-for-the-better-a-definitive-ranking |date=22 December 2015 }}, ''Bustle'', 26 July 2014.</ref> A corset she wore as outerwear during her 1990 [[Blond Ambition World Tour]] sold for US$52,000 in 2012 at the Christie's Pop Culture auction in London.<ref>{{cite web|last=DelliCarpini Jr.|first=Gregory|title=Madonna's Iconic Cone Bra Sells for $52,000|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-hook/473934/madonnas-iconic-cone-bra-sells-for-52000|date=3 December 2012|access-date=21 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130820055259/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-hook/473934/madonnas-iconic-cone-bra-sells-for-52000|archive-date=20 August 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Versace]]'s autumn 2013 couture collection featured fashions that were open in the front, revealing underwire bras.<ref>{{cite web|last=O'Connor|first=Maureen|title=Everyone Is Showing the Centers of Their Bras|url=http://nymag.com/thecut/2013/07/everyone-is-showing-the-centers-of-their-bras.html|website=New York|date=2 July 2013|access-date=22 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130707050410/http://nymag.com/thecut/2013/07/everyone-is-showing-the-centers-of-their-bras.html|archive-date=7 July 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It became fashionable from the early 1990s to wear clothing that showed bra straps.<ref>{{cite news |last=Armstrong |first=Aurora Mackey |date=11 April 1991 |title=Underwear Is In |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-04-11/news/vl-307_1_bra-straps |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=8 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222074751/http://articles.latimes.com/1991-04-11/news/vl-307_1_bra-straps |archive-date=22 December 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bra Turns Hundred This Year|url=http://www.lifeinitaly.com/fashion/bra-history.asp|publisher=Life in Italy|accessdate=23 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130429151011/http://www.lifeinitaly.com/fashion/bra-history.asp|archive-date=29 April 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Show off Our Straps|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-08-14/news/0308140423_1_bra-straps-beads-spaghetti-strap-dress|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=14 August 2003|access-date=22 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029211443/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-08-14/news/0308140423_1_bra-straps-beads-spaghetti-strap-dress|archive-date=29 October 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Warren|first=Ellen|title=Playing Peekaboo|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-08-05/news/sc-cons-0805-ellen-warren-bra-straps-20100804_1_bra-straps-fashion-statement-underwear|work=Chicago Tribune|date=5 August 2010|access-date=22 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823112019/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-08-05/news/sc-cons-0805-ellen-warren-bra-straps-20100804_1_bra-straps-fashion-statement-underwear|archive-date=23 August 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  \n\nWearing clothes that reveal the bra or straps became so common that ''Cosmopolitan'' created guidelines in 2012 on how to expose them. Advice included avoiding plain, flesh-toned, smooth-cup bras, so that the exposure does not appear accidental; making sure the bra is in good condition; and wearing a style that either matches the colour of the outerwear or is dramatically different.<ref name=cosmor22Aug>{{cite magazine|last=Cardellino|first=Carly|title=How to Show Off Your Bra in Style|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/celebrity/news/selena-gomez-shows-off-her-bra|magazine=Cosmopolitan|date=25 July 2012|access-date=22 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130716173007/http://www.cosmopolitan.com/celebrity/news/selena-gomez-shows-off-her-bra|archive-date=16 July 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Decreasing Western usage ===\n\nWhile a few women have a medical and surgical need to wear a brassiere, informal surveys have found that many women began wearing bras to be fashionable, to conform to social or maternal pressure, or for physical support. Very few cited comfort as the reason. In fact, many women experience so much discomfort that they remove their bra as soon as they can. Many Western women recognize that they have been socialized to wear bras, and some who choose to go without report feeling exposed or \"subject to violation\".<ref name=adams>{{cite news|last=Adams|first=Stephen|title=Bad Back, Neck Pain and Headaches: The Perils of Wearing a Poorly Fitting Bra|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/9675935/Bad-back-neck-pain-and-headaches-the-perils-of-wearing-a-poorly-fitting-bra.html|date=13 November 2012|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=8 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207230509/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/9675935/Bad-back-neck-pain-and-headaches-the-perils-of-wearing-a-poorly-fitting-bra.html|archive-date=7 December 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{sfnm |1a1=Burns-Ardolino |1y=2007 |1pp=30\u201332 |2a1=Sischo|2y=2008|2p=58}}<ref name=angel/> \n\nIn Western society, there is an increasing trend towards [[bralessness]] among a number of women, especially millennials, who have expressed opposition to and are giving up wearing bras.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mallenbaum |first1=Carly |title=Why Millennials are going braless |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2016/07/19/braless-millenials-bralette/87111292/ |website=USA TODAY |accessdate=20 September 2018 |language=en |date=19 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920084248/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2016/07/19/braless-millenials-bralette/87111292/ |archive-date=2018-09-20 |url-status=live }}</ref> Being seen in public while not wearing a bra is becoming more acceptable, encouraging more women to go without. In 2016, ''[[Allure (magazine)|Allure]]'' magazine fashion director Rachael Wang wrote, \"Going braless is as old as feminism but it seems to be bubbling to the surface more recently as a direct response to [[Third-wave feminism|Third Wave]] moments like [[Free the Nipple (campaign)|#freethenipple]] hashtag campaign, increased trans-visibility like [[Caitlyn Jenner]]'s ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' cover ... and [[Lena Dunham]]\u2019s show ''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]]'' (which features young girls often without bras).\"<ref name=mallenbaum>{{cite web |last1=Mallenbaum |first1=Carly |title=Why Millennials are going braless |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2016/07/19/braless-millenials-bralette/87111292/ |website=USA TODAY |accessdate=16 September 2018 |language=en |date=19 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920084248/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2016/07/19/braless-millenials-bralette/87111292/ |archive-date=2018-09-20 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Brooke Sweat and Jennifer Fopma at Hermosa Beach 2012 (2) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Back view and front view of [[sports bra]]s worn by US [[beach volleyball]] players]]\n\nIn an online survey for ''[[All You]]'' magazine in 2013, 25 per cent of women reported that they do not wear a bra every day.<ref name=usigan>{{cite web|last1=Usigan|first1=Ysolt|title=The Results of Our Bra Survey: How Often Do You Wear a Bra and Wash Your Bras? Plus, How Much You Spend on One?|url=http://dailysavings.allyou.com/2013/04/25/results-bra-survey/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502004716/http://dailysavings.allyou.com/2013/04/25/results-bra-survey/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 May 2013|publisher=All You|date=25 April 2013}}</ref> Surveys have reported that 5\u201325 per cent of Western women do not wear a bra.<ref name=independent15aug>{{Cite news|last=Walsh|first=John|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/breast-supporting-act-a-century-of-the-bra-5334510.html|title=Breast Supporting Act: A Century of the Bra|date=15 August 2007|work=The Independent|accessdate=11 May 2010|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305101134/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/breast-supporting-act-a-century-of-the-bra-5334510.html|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1stbras.com/Bra_Cup_Sizes.html|title=Bra Cup Sizes\u2014Getting Fitted with the Right Size|publisher=1stbras.com|accessdate=11 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218132215/http://www.1stbras.com/Bra_Cup_Sizes.html|archivedate=18 February 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liv.com/right_bra.php|title=The Right Bra|publisher=Liv.com|accessdate=11 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090328083521/http://www.liv.com/right_bra.php|archivedate=28 March 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  \nA National [[No Bra Day]] was first observed in the United States on 9 July 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=July 9, 2012 Is the Second Annual 'National No Bra Day'|url=http://kygl.com/july-9-2012-is-the-second-annual-national-no-bra-day/|accessdate=14 September 2012|date=9 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815101041/http://kygl.com/july-9-2012-is-the-second-annual-national-no-bra-day/|archive-date=15 August 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Women posted on Twitter about the relief they felt when taking off their bra.<ref>{{cite news|title=No Bra Day: Women Tweet About the Merits of Not Wearing Lingerie|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/09/no-bra-day-tweets-women_n_1659541.html|accessdate=14 September 2012|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=9 July 2012|first=Emma|last=Gray|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120713060647/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/09/no-bra-day-tweets-women_n_1659541.html|archive-date=13 July 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> More than 250,000 people expressed an interest in \"attending\" the day on a Facebook page.<ref>{{cite web|title=National No Bra Day gains support, boosts spirits|url=http://now.msn.com/national-no-bra-day-gains-support-boosts-spirits|accessdate=14 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120715235024/http://now.msn.com/national-no-bra-day-gains-support-boosts-spirits|archive-date=15 July 2012}}</ref> No Bra Day is now observed internationally on 13 October.<ref name=independent15aug/>\n\nA [[Harris Insights & Analytics|Harris Poll]] commissioned by ''[[Playtex]]'' asked more than 1,000 women what they like in a bra. Among the respondents, 67 per cent said they prefer wearing a bra to going braless, while 85 per cent wanted to wear a \"shape-enhancing bra that feels like nothing at all.\" They were split as regards underwire bras: 49 per cent said they prefer underwire bras, the same percentage as those who said they prefer wireless bras.{{sfn|Luciani|2009|p=224}} According to underwire manufacturer S & S Industries of New York, who supply bras to [[Victoria's Secret]], [[Bali (lingerie)|Bali]], [[Warner's]], [[Playtex]], [[VF Corporation|Vanity Fair]], and other labels, about 70 per cent of bra-wearing women wear underwire bras.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thepowerhour.com/news/fashion_airports.htm|title=Functional Fashion Helps Some Through Airport Checkpoints|last=Goo|first=Sara Kehaulani|date=10 December 2004|website=The Washington Post|accessdate=17 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130185633/http://thepowerhour.com/news/fashion_airports.htm|archive-date=30 November 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Third-world usage ===\n\nBras are not universally worn around the world; in some third-world countries bras may cost up to 10\u201330 hours of a woman's wages, making them unaffordable to most of the population.<ref name=hooked/><ref name=hinson>{{cite news|last1=Hinson|first1=Tamara|title=The Breast Way to Support Women in Africa|url=http://metro.co.uk/2012/04/01/the-breast-way-to-support-women-in-africa-373675/|publisher=Metro|date=1 April 2012|access-date=1 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710174809/http://metro.co.uk/2012/04/01/the-breast-way-to-support-women-in-africa-373675/|archive-date=10 July 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=frip/> {{asof|2011}}, women in [[Fiji]] needed to pay up to a week's wages for a new bra.<ref name=haxton>{{cite web|last1=Haxton|first1=Nance|title=Fijian Bra Program Sparks Charity Debate|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2008-08-02/fijian-bra-program-sparks-charity-debate/461632|accessdate=2 July 2015|date=25 May 2011|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702235008/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2008-08-02/fijian-bra-program-sparks-charity-debate/461632|archive-date=2 July 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Bras are highly prized at second-hand markets in [[West Africa]].<ref name=hinson/><ref name=frip>{{cite web|title=Frip Ethique|url=https://bosomgalore.com/frip-ethique/|website=Bosom Galore Lingerie|accessdate=1 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725113024/https://bosomgalore.com/frip-ethique/|archivedate=25 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Uplift Project provides recycled bras to women in developing countries.<ref>{{cite web|title=Uplift Bras|url=http://www.upliftbras.org/|accessdate=1 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150803091250/http://www.upliftbras.org/|archive-date=3 August 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Since 2005 they have shipped 330,000, including to Fiji, Vanuatu, Tonga, and Cambodia.<ref name=hooked>{{cite web|title=Hooked on Bra Collection|url=http://www.times.co.nz/news/hooked-on-bra-collection.html|publisher=Times of New Zealand|accessdate=1 July 2015|date=22 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701133030/http://www.times.co.nz/news/hooked-on-bra-collection.html|archivedate=1 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 Somalia's hard-line Islamic group [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabaab]] forced women to shake their breasts at gunpoint to see if they were wearing bras, which they called \"un-Islamic\".<ref name=radiocanada/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/oddlyEnoughNews/idAFTRE59F1K420091016?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0|title=Somali Islamists Whip Women for Wearing Bras|date=16 October 2009|agency=Reuters|access-date=8 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211120303/http://af.reuters.com/article/oddlyEnoughNews/idAFTRE59F1K420091016?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0|archive-date=11 February 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A resident of [[Mogadishu]] whose daughters were whipped said, \"The Islamists say a woman's chest should be firm naturally, or flat.\"<ref name=radiocanada>{{cite web|title=Fouett\u00e9es pour un soutien-gorge|language=fr|trans-title=Lashes for a Bra|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/International/2009/10/16/008-somalie-soutien-gorge.shtml|website=Radio-Canada Info|publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Radio-Canada|agency=Reuters|accessdate=4 February 2012|date=16 October 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916010907/http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/International/2009/10/16/008-somalie-soutien-gorge.shtml|archive-date=16 September 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Economic impact ===\nConsumers spend around $16&nbsp;billion a year worldwide on bras.<ref name=redbook/> In the US during 2012, women owned an average of nine bras and wore six on a regular basis.<ref name=redbook>{{cite web|title=Victoria's Secrets: 6 Surprising Bra Stats|url=http://www.redbookmag.com/beauty-fashion/tips-advice/fun-bra-facts|publisher=Redbook. Magazine|accessdate=8 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103161009/http://www.redbookmag.com/beauty-fashion/tips-advice/fun-bra-facts|archive-date=3 January 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> That increased from 2006, when the average American woman owned six, one of which was strapless, and one in a colour other than white.{{sfn|Acton|Adams|Packer|2006|p=38}} British women in a 2009 survey reported that they owned an average of 16 bras.<ref name=guardian1117>{{cite news |last=Fisher |first=Alice |date=15 May 2010 |title=Why Are British Women's Breasts Getting Bigger? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/may/16/womens-breasts-are-getting-bigger |work=The Observer |location=London |publisher=Guardian Media Group |page=44 |issn=0029-7712 |access-date=24 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825002833/https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/may/16/womens-breasts-are-getting-bigger |archive-date=25 August 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe average bra size among North American women has changed from 34B in 1983 to a 34DD in 2012\u20132013,<ref name=racked>{{cite web|first=Erika|last=Graham|date=22 July 2013|title=The Average American Bra Size Is Now a 34 DD|url=http://racked.com/archives/2013/07/22/bra-size-increase.php|website=Racked|accessdate=30 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130822201653/http://racked.com/archives/2013/07/22/bra-size-increase.php|archive-date=22 August 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and from 36C in 2013 to 36DD in the UK during 2014\u20132015.<ref name=crook>{{cite web|last1=Crook|first1=Nicola Rodney|title=The Great British Bra Survey Results|url=http://www.brasandhoney.com/blog/2015/09/16/the-great-british-bra-survey-results/|publisher=Bras and Honey|accessdate=17 November 2015|date=16 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118194052/http://www.brasandhoney.com/blog/2015/09/16/the-great-british-bra-survey-results/|archive-date=18 November 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The change in bra size has been linked to growing obesity rates, breast implants, increased birth control usage, estrogen mimicking pollutants, the availability of a larger selection of bras, and women wearing better fitting bras.<ref name=racked/><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/hardy-jones/toxic-chemicals-fish_b_1258231.html | work=The Huffington Post | first=Hardy | last=Jones | title=Larger Breast Size, Obesity and Diabetes Tied to Estrogen-Mimicking Pollutants | date=9 February 2012 | access-date=31 October 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111125340/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/hardy-jones/toxic-chemicals-fish_b_1258231.html | archive-date=11 November 2013 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bra shirt and same with viscose wrap dress.jpg|thumb|Bra shirt with built-in breast support (on left), 2015]]\nBras are made in Asian countries, including Sri Lanka, India, and China. While there has been some social pressure from the [[anti-sweatshop movement|anti-sweatshop]] and [[anti-globalization movement]]s on manufacturers to reduce use of [[sweatshop]] labour, most major apparel manufacturers rely on them directly and indirectly.  Prior to 2005, a trade agreement limited textile imports to the European Union and the US. China was exporting US$33.9 billion in textiles and clothing each year to the EU and the US. When those quotas expired on 1 January 2005, the so-called Bra Wars began. Within six months, China shipped 30 million more bras to the two markets: 33 per cent more to the US and 63 per cent more to the EU.<ref name=watson>{{cite web|last1=Watson|first1=Noshua|title=MAS Holdings: Strategic Corporate Social Responsibility in the Apparel Industry|url=http://www.unprme.org/reports/masholdingsfinalinseadcasefeb28th2006.pdf|publisher=INSEAD|accessdate=1 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160108235002/http://www.unprme.org/reports/masholdingsfinalinseadcasefeb28th2006.pdf|archive-date=8 January 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> {{asof|2014}}, an average bra cost \u00a329.80.<ref>{{cite web|title=Average Price of Bras and Knickers in the United Kingdom (UK) in 2012 and 2014* (in GBP)|url=http://www.statista.com/statistics/427019/bras-and-knickers-average-price-united-kingdom-uk/|publisher=Statistica|accessdate=2 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702162122/http://www.statista.com/statistics/427019/bras-and-knickers-average-price-united-kingdom-uk/|archive-date=2 July 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> {{asof|2012}}, Africa imported US$107 million worth of bras, with South Africa accounting for 40 per cent. Morocco was second and Nigeria third, while Mauritius topped purchasing on a [[per capita]] basis.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mungai|first=Christine|title=The Plus-Size tax: Women Who Buy Bigger Bras Tend to Spend More, So What Does It Reveal About Africa?|url=http://mgafrica.com/article/2014-11-13-the-plus-size-tax-women-who-buy-bigger-bra-sizes-tend-to-spend-more|publisher=Mail and Guardian Africa|accessdate=2 July 2015|date=14 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702160840/http://mgafrica.com/article/2014-11-13-the-plus-size-tax-women-who-buy-bigger-bra-sizes-tend-to-spend-more|archive-date=2 July 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn countries where labour costs are low, bras that cost US$5\u20137 to manufacture sell for US$50 or more in American retail stores. {{asof|2006}}, female garment workers in Sri Lanka earned about US$2.20 per day.<ref name=watson/> Similarly, Honduran garment factory workers in 2003 were paid US$0.24 for each $50 [[Sean John]] sweatshirt they made, less than one-half of one per cent of the retail price.<ref name=\"seanjohn\">{{cite web| title =Sean John Setisa Report| publisher =[[National Labor Committee]]|date=October 2003| url =http://www.nlcnet.org/article.php?id=103| accessdate =31 May 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070522173501/http://www.nlcnet.org/article.php?id=103 |archivedate = 22 May 2007}}</ref> In 2009, residents in the textile manufacturing city of [[Gurao, Shantou|Gurao]] in the [[Guangdong]] province of China made more than 200 million bras. Children were employed to assemble bras and were paid 0.30 [[Chinese yuan|yuan]] for every 100 bra straps they helped assemble. In one day they could earn 20 to 30 yuan.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Dirty Secret Behind Jeans and Bras|url=http://www.greenpeace.org/eastasia/news/stories/toxics/2010/textile-pollution-xintang-gurao/|accessdate=1 July 2015|date=1 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711065413/http://www.greenpeace.org/eastasia/news/stories/toxics/2010/textile-pollution-xintang-gurao/|archive-date=11 July 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Western Feminist opinions ===\n\nIn 1968 at the feminist [[Miss America protest]], protesters symbolically threw a number of feminine products into a \"Freedom Trash Can\". These included bras,{{sfn|Dow|2003}} which were among items the protesters called \"instruments of female torture\"<ref name=\"Duffett 1968, p. 4\">{{cite magazine |last=Duffett |first=Judith |date=October 1968 |title=WLM vs. Miss America |magazine=Voice of the Women's Liberation Movement |page=4}}</ref> and accouterments of what they perceived to be enforced [[femininity]]. A local news story in the Atlantic City ''Press'' erroneously reported that \"the bras, girdles, falsies, curlers, and copies of popular women's magazines burned in the 'Freedom Trash Can'\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Boucher |first=John L. |title=Bra-Burners Blitz Boardwalk |work=(Atlantic City) Press |date=8 September 1968}}</ref>{{sfn|Campbell|2010|pp=109\u2013110}} Individuals who were present said that no one burned a bra nor did anyone take off her bra.<ref name=\"Duffett 1968, p. 4\"/>{{sfn|Collins|2003}} However, a female reporter (Lindsy Van Gelder) covering the protest drew an analogy between the feminist protesters and [[Vietnam War]] protesters who [[draft-card burning|burned their draft cards]], and the parallel between protesters burning their draft cards and women burning their bras was encouraged by some organizers including [[Robin Morgan]]. \"The media picked up on the bra part\", [[Carol Hanisch]] said later. \"I often say that if they had called us 'girdle burners,' every woman in America would have run to join us.\"{{sfn|Collins|2003}}<ref name=Greenfieldboyce>{{cite web|last=Greenfieldboyce|first=Nell|title=Pageant Protest Sparked Bra-Burning Myth|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=94240375&from=mobile|publisher=NPR|accessdate=6 February 2012|date=5 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109083508/http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=94240375&from=mobile|archive-date=9 November 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFeminism and \"bra-burning\" became linked in popular culture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://radioequalizer.blogspot.com/2006/09/rush-limbaugh-gloria-steinem-jane.html |publisher=Radio Equalizer |date=14 September 2006 |title=Rush Blasts Greenstone |access-date=8 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616231246/http://radioequalizer.blogspot.com/2006/09/rush-limbaugh-gloria-steinem-jane.html |archive-date=16 June 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://heuriskein.blogspot.com/2006/01/so-called-ginsburg-standard.html |publisher=heuriskein |date=9 January 2006 |title=The So-Called 'Ginsburg Standard' |access-date=8 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616231251/http://heuriskein.blogspot.com/2006/01/so-called-ginsburg-standard.html |archive-date=16 June 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The analogous term ''jockstrap-burning'' has since been coined as a reference to [[masculism]].<ref name=\"jockburning\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-07-31/news/mn-29889_1_male-contraception|title=Search for Male Contraceptive Makes Gains|access-date=8 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217063442/http://articles.latimes.com/1995-07-31/news/mn-29889_1_male-contraception|archive-date=17 February 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> While feminist women did not literally burn their bras, some stopped wearing them in protest.{{sfn|Kornblum|2011}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hipmama.com/node/755 |title=Motherhood, Feminism and the Graveyard of Unwearable Bras |first=Violet A. |last=Shearer |accessdate=7 April 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61CnjNVJO?url=http://www.hipmama.com/node/755 |archive-date=25 August 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The feminist author Bonnie J. Dow has suggested that the association between feminism and bra-burning was encouraged by individuals who opposed the feminist movement.{{sfn|Dow|2003}} \"Bra-burning\" created an image that women weren't really seeking freedom from sexism, but were attempting to assert themselves as sexual beings.{{sfn|Dow|2003|p=130}} This might lead individuals to believe, as [[Susan J. Douglas]] wrote, that the women were merely trying to be \"trendy, and to attract men.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Douglas |first=Susan |author-link=Susan J. Douglas |year=1994 |title=Where the Girls Are: Growing Up Female with the Mass Media |location=New York |publisher=Random House |page=160}} Cited in {{harvnb|Dow|2003|p=130}}.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/unknown/viewarticle.aspx?id=299050 |author=Loughran, Jane |title=You Don't Have to Be a Bra-Burning Feminist to Want to Keep Your Name |publisher=News & Star |date=11 January 2005 |access-date=8 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927230647/http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/unknown/viewarticle.aspx?id=299050 |archive-date=27 September 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://menz.org.nz/menz-issues/october-1996 |last=Williams |first=Ginny |title=Women of Goodwill |publisher=MENZ Issues |date=October 1996 |volume=1 |issue=4 |access-date=8 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717013212/https://menz.org.nz/menz-issues/october-1996/ |archive-date=17 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>{{sfnm |1a1=Campo |1y=2005 |2a1=Spongberg |2y=1993}} Some feminist activists believe that [[anti-feminist]]s use the bra burning myth and the subject of going braless to trivialize what the protesters were trying to accomplish at the feminist 1968 [[Miss America protest]] and the feminist movement in general.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lee |first=Jennifer |date=11 June 2014 |title=Feminism Has a Bra-Burning Myth Problem |url=http://time.com/2853184/feminism-has-a-bra-burning-myth-problem |website=Time |location=New York |access-date=24 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723220901/http://time.com/2853184/feminism-has-a-bra-burning-myth-problem/ |archive-date=23 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>{{sfn|Dow|1999}}<ref name=burnbra>{{cite web|url=http://www.snopes.com/history/american/burnbra.htm |title=Red Hot Mamas (bra-burning) |publisher=Snopes.com Urban Legends}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Trope (philosophy)|trope]] of feminists burning their bras was anticipated by an earlier generation of feminists who called for burning corsets as a step toward liberation. In 1873 [[Elizabeth Stuart Phelps Ward]] wrote:\n\n{{quote|So burn up the corsets!&nbsp;... No, nor do you save the whalebones, you will never need whalebones again.  Make a bonfire of the cruel steels that have lorded it over your thorax and abdomens for so many years and heave a sigh of relief, for your emancipation I assure you, from this moment has begun.{{sfn|Phelps|1873|p=79}}}}\n\nSome feminists began arguing in the 1960s and 1970s that the bra was an example of how women's clothing shaped and even deformed women's bodies to male expectations. Professor [[Lisa Jardine]] listened to feminist [[Germaine Greer]] talk about bras during a formal college dinner in [[Newnham College, Cambridge]], in 1964 (Greer had become a member of that college in 1962):\n\n{{quote|At the graduates' table, Germaine was explaining that there could be no liberation for women, no matter how highly educated, as long as we were required to cram our breasts into bras constructed like mini-Vesuviuses, two stitched white cantilevered cones which bore no resemblance to the female anatomy. The willingly suffered discomfort of the Sixties bra, she opined vigorously, was a hideous symbol of female oppression.<ref name=dangermouth>{{Cite news |first=Stephanie |last=Merritt |author-link=Stephanie Merritt |url=http://books.guardian.co.uk/departments/politicsphilosophyandsociety/story/0,6000,1057077,00.html |title=Danger Mouth |work=The Observer |date=5 October 2003 |access-date=5 January 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080418060254/http://books.guardian.co.uk/departments/politicsphilosophyandsociety/story/0,6000,1057077,00.html |archive-date=18 April 2008 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>}}\n\n[[Germaine Greer]]'s book ''[[The Female Eunuch]]'' (1970) became associated with the anti-bra movement because she pointed out how restrictive and uncomfortable a bra could be.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.biographyonline.net/writers/germaine-greer.html | title=German Greer Biography | accessdate=7 April 2010 | archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61Cnil4GK?url=http://www.biographyonline.net/writers/germaine-greer.html | archive-date=25 August 2011 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> \"Bras are a ludicrous invention\", she wrote, \"but if you make bralessness a rule, you're just subjecting yourself to yet another repression.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Greer |first=Germaine |author-link=Germaine Greer |year=2009 |title=The Female Eunuch |location=New York |publisher=HarperCollins|title-link=The Female Eunuch }}</ref>\n\n[[Susan Brownmiller]] in her book ''Femininity'' (1984) took the position that women without bras shock and anger men because men \"implicitly think that they own breasts and that only they should remove bras.\"{{sfn|Young|2005|p=192}}\n\nThe feminist author [[Iris Marion Young]] wrote in 2005 that the bra \"serves as a barrier to touch\" and that a braless woman is \"[[Sexual objectification|deobjectified]]\", eliminating the \"hard, pointy look that phallic culture posits as the norm.\" Without a bra, in her view, women's breasts are not consistently shaped objects but change as the woman moves, reflecting the natural body.{{sfn|Young|2005|p=192}} Other feminist anti-bra arguments from Young in 2005 include that [[training bra]]s are used to indoctrinate girls into thinking about their breasts as sexual objects and to accentuate their sexuality.{{sfn|Young|2005|p=192}} Young also wrote in 2007 that, in American culture, breasts are subject to {{nowrap|\"[c]apitalist,}} [[patriarchy|patriarchal]] American media-dominated culture [that] objectifies breasts before such a distancing glance that freezes and masters.\"<ref>Cited in {{harvnb|Burns-Ardolino|2007|p=31}}.</ref> The academic Wendy Burns-Ardolino wrote in 2007 that women's decision to wear bras is mediated by the \"[[male gaze]]\".{{sfn|Burns-Ardolino|2007|pp=30\u201332}}\n\n==Health==\n=== Fit ===\n\nApparel company Ruby Ribbon surveyed 3,000 women in 2014 in advance of National No Bra Day about their attitudes towards their breasts and bras. Among respondents, 92 percent said they simply want support and comfort and are less interested in sex appeal or fashionable colors and designs. Twenty-one percent rated their bra \"An Enemy \u2013 I wish I had never met her\", and nearly half (46 per cent) answered, \"A Business Partner&nbsp;\u2013 I put up with her\". When asked to describe their bra in one word, the most popular term was \"uncomfortable\".<ref name=prnews>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/ruby-ribbon-asks-3-000-women-whats-your-brama-300729067.html|title=Ruby Ribbon Asks 3,000 Women \"What's Your BRAma?\"|first=Ruby|last=Ribbon|website=www.prnewswire.com}}</ref><ref name=\"elite\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/taking-your-bra-off-after-a-long-day-is-a-mood-science-says-half-of-women-can-relate-12708435|title=Half Of Women Do This One Thing As Soon As They Get Home & You Can Def Relate|first=Julia|last=Guerra|website=Elite Daily}}</ref> Many women look forward to the time of day when they can take off their bra.<ref name=\"elite\"/>\n\nSome women experience generalized breast discomfort and tenderness from [[fibrocystic breast changes]], and their breast tissue is often described as \"lumpy\", \"rope-like\", or \"doughy\".<ref name=NEJM2005>{{cite journal |last1=Santen |first1=RJ |last2=Mansel |first2=R |title=Benign breast disorders. |journal=The New England Journal of Medicine |date=21 July 2005 |volume=353 |issue=3 |pages=275\u201385 |doi=10.1056/NEJMra035692 |pmid=16034013}}</ref> Doctors often recommend that women wear a well-fitted, supportive bra to help resolve the symptoms.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fibrocystic Breast Disease: Causes, Symptoms, and Diagnosis |url=https://www.healthline.com/health/fibrocystic-breast-disease#treatments |website=Healthline |accessdate=10 April 2019 |language=en |date=1 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Fibrosis and Simple Cysts in the Breast {{!}} American Cancer Society |url=https://www.cancer.org/cancer/breast-cancer/non-cancerous-breast-conditions/fibrosis-and-simple-cysts-in-the-breast.html |website=www.cancer.org |accessdate=10 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=Fer2019>{{cite book |last1=Ferri |first1=Fred F. |title=Ferri's Clinical Advisor 2019: 5 Books in 1 |date=2018 |publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences |isbn=9780323550765 |page=548 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=-L5dDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA548 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Exercise ===\n\nBiomechanical studies have demonstrated that, depending on the activity and the size of a woman's breast, when she walks or runs braless, her breasts may move up and down by {{convert|4|to|18|cm}} or more, and also oscillate side to side.<ref name=nhsuk/>\n\nResearchers have also found that as women's breast size increased, they took part in less physical activity, especially vigorous exercise. Few very-large-breasted women jogged, for example. To avoid exercise-related discomfort and pain, medical experts suggest women wear a well-fitted [[sports bra]] during activity.<ref name=nhsuk>{{cite web |title=How a well-fitted sports bra can reduce breast pain |url=https://www.nhs.uk/live-well/exercise/right-sports-bra-can-reduce-breast-pain/ |website=nhs.uk |accessdate=7 March 2019 |language=en |date=30 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Breast sagging ===\n[[File:Ptosis.jpg|thumb|Women with large, sagging breasts have a harder time finding a well-fitting bra and are more likely to experience pain and discomfort]]\n\nWomen sometimes wear bras because they mistakenly believe they prevent breasts from sagging ([[Ptosis (breasts)|ptosis]]) as they get older.<ref name=burn/> Physicians, lingerie saleswomen, teen girls, and adult women used to believe that bras were medically required to support breasts. In a 1952 article in ''Parents' Magazine'', Frank H. Crowell wrote that it was important for teen girls to begin wearing bras early. This would prevent  sagging breasts, stretched blood vessels, and poor circulation later on.<ref name=brumberg>{{cite book |url=http://course1.winona.msus.edu/pjohnson/e111/e111f99/brumberg.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020328155254/http://course1.winona.msus.edu/pjohnson/e111/e111f99/brumberg.htm |isbn=0-679-73529-1 |page=336|title=The Body Project: An Intimate History of American Girls|archivedate=28 March 2002|first=Joan Jacobs |last=Brumberg|year=1998 }}</ref>\n\nThis belief was based on the incorrect idea that since breasts cannot anatomically support themselves, wearing a brassiere makes a difference as a woman ages.<ref name=burn>{{cite web |title=Don't burn your bra just yet |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/health-news/dont-burn-your-bra-just-yet-622008.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=8 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717232012/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/health-news/dont-burn-your-bra-just-yet-622008.html |archive-date=17 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"007b Breast\">{{cite web |url=http://www.007b.com/why_wear_bras.php |title=Female Intelligence Agency: Why Do Women Wear Bras? |publisher=007b Breast |accessdate=10 May 2011 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61Cnk7C8i?url=http://www.007b.com/why_wear_bras.php |archive-date=25 August 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> But researchers, bra manufacturers, and health professionals cannot find any evidence to support the idea that wearing a bra for any amount of time decreases breast sagging.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.007b.com/sagging.php|title=Female Intelligence Agency: What Causes Sagging of Breasts?|publisher=007b Breast|access-date=6 November 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061018091042/http://www.007b.com/sagging.php|archive-date=18 October 2006|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Bra manufacturers are careful to claim that bras only affect the shape of breasts while they are being worn.<ref name=\"007b Breast\"/><ref name=cawthorne>{{cite web|first=Simon|last=Cawthorne|title=Bras, the Bare Facts|publisher=Channel 4|date=November 2000|url=http://breathing.com/articles/brassieres-2.htm|access-date=11 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120713004943/http://breathing.com/articles/brassieres-2.htm|archive-date=13 July 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The key factors influencing breast ptosis over a woman's lifetime are [[cigarette]] smoking, her [[gravidity|number of pregnancies]], [[gravity]], higher [[body mass index]], larger bra cup size, and significant weight gain and loss.<ref name=thompson>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.asj.2008.07.004 |lay-url=http://www.livescience.com/1998-breastfeeding-breasts-sag-study-suggests.html |laysource=LiveScience |laydate=2 November 2007 |title=The Effect of Breastfeeding on Breast Aesthetics |year=2008 |last1=Rinker |first1=B. |last2=Veneracion |first2=M. |last3=Walsh |first3=C. |journal=Aesthetic Surgery Journal |volume=28 |issue=5 |pages=534\u2013537 |pmid=19083576|doi-access=free }}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Rinker|first=Brian|last2=Veneracion|first2=Melissa|last3=Walsh|first3=Catherine P.|date=May 2010|title=Breast ptosis: causes and cure|journal=Annals of Plastic Surgery|volume=64|issue=5|pages=579\u2013584|doi=10.1097/SAP.0b013e3181c39377|issn=1536-3708|pmid=20354434}}</ref>\n\n==See also ==\n{{Portal|Fashion}}\n* [[Bustier]]\n* [[Handbra]]\n* [[Male bra]]\n* [[Pasties]]\n* [[Victorian dress reform]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Footnotes ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{refbegin|35em|indent=yes}}\n: {{cite book\n|last1=Acton\n|first1=Johnny\n|author1-link=John Lyon-Dalberg-Acton, 5th Baron Acton\n|last2=Adams\n|first2=Tania\n|last3=Packer\n|first3=Matt\n|year=2006\n|title=Origin of Everyday Things\n|loc